label chapter5:

    # [Scene: Kade Resilience Lab | Morning]

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, steady strings with a hopeful pluck]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low hum of HVAC; distant gulls and the soft clatter of tools]
    "You arrive with the draft in your head like a folded map—terraces here, adjustable gates there, a wetland ribbon where the old fish lane used to run. The lab smells faintly of ozone and coffee; the"
    "coolness of the interior sharpens your focus. Around the model table, sunlight catches the layers of foamboard and two- and three-dimensional annotations until they look almost like a small, inhabitable map of the future."
    "Theo is already there, hair mussed, glasses low on his nose, surrounded by printouts. He slides a tablet toward you—rainfall projections aligned with drainage curves—and his grin is all elbows and optimism."
    show theo_baines at left:
        zoom 0.7

    theo_baines "Look. If we add vegetated buffers to these berm sections, the modeled peak inundation drops by—get this—twelve percent in that downtown sector. And green roofs give us stocked retention and some urban cooling co-benefits. It's measurable, fundable."
    "You lean in, fingertips resting against the cool edge of the table. The graphs are tidy, almost smiling. Numbers have always been your anchor; their promise feels good and dangerous in equal measure."
    show maya_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "Twelve percent buys cred with procurement. But we need metrics that funders trust—what's the confidence interval?"

    theo_baines "Tight enough. I've cross-checked sensors and historical runs. We can present both the model and an on-site pilot metric. It becomes a conditional: funding releases as the pilot meets drainage thresholds."
    "He taps the tablet, and the projection lifts—a translucent overlay of green ribbons and berms across the boardwalk model. The motion steadies something in your chest."

    menu:
        "Point to the pilot metric and say 'this is our leverage'":
            "You tap the projection and feel the hum of possibility. Theo brightens—his data becomes the spear you can hand to procurement. It promises speed and a clear handshake with funders."
        "Insist we fold explicit job guarantees into the funding language":
            "You set your palm on the paper where a row of tiny, hand-drawn figures now seems to represent real people. Theo hesitates, then nods—this complicates the headline numbers but frames impact in a way that feels anchored to the neighborhood."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both routes leave a pleasant heat in your face; both feel like truth—one technical, one humane."
    "The pause leaves a pleasant heat in your face. Both routes feel like truth: one technical, one humane. Before you can settle, Sienna appears at the far end of the table—precise as ever, the titanium pen tapping a rhythm against her palm."
    hide theo_baines
    hide maya_calder

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Pen tap]
    show dr_sienna_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_sienna_kade "Your amendments read better than I expected.' (She lets the sentence hang.) 'If Procurement can see a verifiable reduction in projected inundation—specific percentages, clear metrics—we can fast-track approval. Quarter timeline. The caveat is, we need to hit the benchmarks in the first six months."
    "You hear the carefulness beneath her tone: urgency braided with policy muscle. It's the offer you half-feared and half-anticipated. Her gaze is steady, unreadable in that way that used to unsettle you; now it steadies you because it contains the thing you need."
    show maya_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "Six months is tight. But a pilot coupled with a monitoring clause could do it. It has to include community input on where those terraces go, and commitments for local hires to build and maintain them."
    "Dr. Sienna Kade: (a small shift, not quite a smile) 'I can write liaison positions into the operational plan—if you can guarantee metrics. Procurement won't fund sentiment; they fund reduced risk. Give me numbers, and I'll give you speed.'"
    "The two of you trade a long look—one of negotiation where neither of you yields much but both offer pieces that fit together. The lab's humidity presses at the windows; outside, a gull cries like punctuation."
    "Elias 'Eli' Maren's voice carries in from the adjacent workshop—a bright, off-key rhythm over the thump of a hammer. He is halfway through nailing planters into a boarded window, string lights looped like a jaunty halo around his shoulders. The sound cuts the seriousness with a domestic, human note."
    "Elias 'Eli' Maren: (singing) 'We plant what clings, we plant what holds, we'll sing when the harbor cold gets old—' (he laughs) '—Maya, you've got to promise me the strings get solar bulbs.'"
    "You smile despite yourself. Eli's lightness is a tether; you can almost feel the pull of the promenade when his laughter reaches you."
    "You walk over to the workshop doorway; sawdust beads the air and the smell of wet wood is comforting in a way numbers cannot be. Eli hands you a strip of reclaimed timber—it's smooth where a nail used to be."

    "Elias 'Eli' Maren" "If you need someone to make the terraces look like a party, I'm your person. I can't do your data, but I can make the spaces people want to live in."

    maya_calder "Then make them irresistible. We need faces as much as metrics."

    "Elias 'Eli' Maren" "Faces are my specialty. Also, free music for any ribbon-cutting."
    "There's a pause where you both imagine that small, silly celebration. It feels like a promise."

    menu:
        "Take the timber and sketch a small community planting area on the model":
            "You rough-sketched a play area into a berm depression. Eli's grin gets wider; the model suddenly has a suggestion of life—tiny modeled plants, a bench. Theo nods; even the numbers look friendlier."
        "Leave the timber and return to talk numbers with Theo":
            "You let the timber rest. Back at the table, the graphs wait like maps; choosing them doesn't feel like denying joy, but like reserving it for a future you need to earn."

    # --- merge ---
    "You breathe in, choosing both the technical and the human in the flicker of a second."
    "You breathe in, choosing both the technical and the human in the flicker of a second. The lab buzzes—people moving, coffee punctuating conversation—and the feeling that this is work worth waking up for lifts your chest. Outside, the harbor light is small but patient."
    "Your phone vibrates. Rosa's name flashes. You answer, and her voice fills the line: warm, slow, the cadence of someone who has hauled nets through a thousand dawns."

    "Rosa (phone)" "Maya. I was walking the old lane yesterday—found a place where the old stones still curve like a shoulder. Your father used to cut through there when the fog was thick. If they put a wall like a closed door, folk will lose those shortcuts. We need steps. We need the ladder places, not cliffs."
    "Her words pull a map from memory: the narrow gully steps, the way neighbors traded gossip on the stairs, the fish smell in winter that meant someone had come home. There is a ache and a warmth to it all."

    maya_calder "We'll keep alleys, Rosa. We'll make passages—gates that can open, terraces that double as steps. We can measure their effectiveness for flood control and keep them as living lanes."
    "Rosa: (a laugh, sharp with pride) 'All right, then. Don't let them take the lanes.'"
    "You end the call with conviction threaded through your chest. The community voice raw and real in your ear steadies you in a way that charts never will."

    dr_sienna_kade "We can build gates that function as thresholds—openable for daily flow, closed for storms. The engineering is sound."

    maya_calder "And the funding?"

    dr_sienna_kade "Conditional. Metrics tie to release. Pilot success unlocks quarter-funding, which then unlocks scaled procurement. You get a fast track if you commit to leading the pilot."
    "Theo leans in, pointing at a cluster of figures where green roofs intersect with berm placement."
    show theo_baines at center:
        zoom 0.7

    theo_baines "If you lead the pilot, we can make data visible, transparent. Real-time sensors, community dashboards. Funders like certainty—as long as they can watch the certainty appear."
    "Your chest tightens with the sense that agency is not a single lever but many small ones wired together. You can feel the swell of possibility—the lab's resources, Sienna's corridors of power, Theo's numbers, Eli's hands, Rosa's memory—braiding into a rope that could hold."
    "You pace the model table, palms on foamboard, and imagine spending the quarter touring roofs, walking alleys, teaching a group to read a sensor graph like a tide. You imagine mortar and music and the smell"
    "of wet soil on your gloves. There's a rising warmth to it; the decision before you is not whether to act but how to use the influence you've been granted."
    "Dr. Sienna Kade watches you, face unreadable in the way that once felt cold and now feels like a mirror."

    dr_sienna_kade "We have a window. I can open it—but not without evidence. Will you deliver that?"

    maya_calder "I'll deliver something funders can count and neighbors can stand on."
    "Dr. Sienna Kade: (a pause) 'Then let's draft the pilot metrics and liaison positions. I'll move Procurement. But the timeline will be unforgiving. Are you prepared for that pace?'"
    "The lab hum seems to condense into the space between breaths. You are prepared—prepared enough—and the preparing has filled you with a kind of steady fire."
    "Your hand rests on the stack of printouts. You can smell the ink and the faint salt from the harbor that clings to your jacket. Everything aligns: a responsible-sounding plan, a funding lever, and the promise of community work done on the ground."
    "In that charged quiet, your choices fan out in your mind like paths through a tidal marsh—each promising progress, each asking a price."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings swell, hopeful and bright]
    "You feel the rise of agency as a current beneath your feet. The choice is yours to channel institutional power: toward explicit community safeguards and jobs, toward maximal technical efficiency to win the fastest funding, or toward a risky public hold that forces broader participation. Each is a way forward."
    # [Scene: Boardroom / model table | Morning]
    hide dr_sienna_kade
    hide maya_calder
    hide theo_baines

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant exhale of the city outside, as if the harbor itself waits]
    "You straighten, look from Sienna to Theo to Eli, and realize that the negotiation you've lived in fragments is now a single, decisive motion away from being cast into policy. It hums like sunlight on wet metal: possible, urgent, almost within reach."

    menu:
        "Push for community protections and job guarantees embedded in funding.":
            jump chapter6
